revision.text:
'''Copyright law of North Korea''' is regulated by the Copyright Act of 2001.<ref name="Seoul2002–122">{{cite book|author=Yonhap News Agency, Seoul|title=North Korea Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIlh9nNeadMC&pg=PA122|date=27 December 2002|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-3523-5|page=122}}</ref> It introduced a 50 years [[Post mortem auctoris|pma]] protection, and has been amended several times.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wipo.int/wipolex/en/details.jsp?id=9722|title=Democratic People's Republic of Korea: Copyright Law of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (as amended by Decree No. 1532 of February 1, 2006, of the Presidium of the Supreme People's Assembly)|website=www.wipo.int|access-date=2016-05-23}}</ref>

[[North Korea]] had no copyright law before that date.<ref name="Seoul2002–222">{{cite book|author=Yonhap News Agency, Seoul|title=North Korea Handbook|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIlh9nNeadMC&pg=PA222|date=27 December 2002|publisher=M.E. Sharpe|isbn=978-0-7656-3523-5|page=222}}</ref>

North Korea is party to the [[Berne Convention]] since 2003.<ref name="Gervais2010">{{cite book|author=Daniel J. Gervais|title=Collective Management of Copyright and Related Rights|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6we-5dIahwkC&pg=PA454|year=2010|publisher=Kluwer Law International|isbn=978-90-411-2724-2|page=454}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.jtbc.joins.com/article/article.aspx?news_id=NB11218004|title=조선중앙TV에 저작권료 지불? 확인해보니|publisher=JTBC}}</ref>

