A '''false lien''' is document that purports to describe a [[lien]], but which has no legal basis, based upon false, fictitious, or fraudulent statements or representations. The filing of false liens has been used as a tool of harassment in "[[paper terrorism]]", often against government officials. The practice was pioneered by the [[Posse Comitatus (organization)|Posse Comitatus]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.adl.org/mwd/privlien.asp|title=Paper Terrorism's Forgotten Victims: The Use of Bogus Liens against Private Individuals and Businesses|author=Mark Pitcavage|date=June 29, 1998|publisher=Anti-Defamation League}}</ref> The [[Bureau of Prisons]] has responded by treating lien documents and personal information (such as [[Social Security Number]]s) of federal agents, judges, etc. as [[contraband]] in [[federal prison]]s.
The U.S. Congress has criminalized the filing of false liens,<ref>{{usc|18|1521}}</ref> and the [[U.S. Sentencing Guidelines]] treat the filing of a false lien against a government official as equally serious as [[threatening the government officials of the United States]].<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a6_1.htm|title=§2A6.1. Threatening or Harassing Communications; Hoaxes; False Liens|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100618204634/http://www.ussc.gov/2009guid/2a6_1.htm|archivedate=2010-06-18|df=}}</ref> Various U.S. states have been developing ways of combating false liens.<ref>{{citation|title="Lien on Me": State Policy Innovation in Response to Paper Terrorism|author=Robert Chamberlain and Donald P. Haider-Markel|publisher=Political Research Quarterly|volume=58|number=3|date=Sep 2005|pages=449–460}}</ref>
