{{no refs|date=June 2015}} {{Expand German|Schloss Glienicke|date=September 2014}} {{Infobox building | name = Glienicke Palace | native_name = Schloss Glienicke | former_names = | alternate_names = | image = Schloss Glienicke Süden.jpg | alt = | caption = Glienicke Palace | map_type = Germany | map_alt = | map_caption = Location in Germany | altitude = | building_type = [[Palace]] | architectural_style = [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] | structural_system = | cost = | client = [[Carl of Prussia]] | owner = ''[[Prussian Palaces and Gardens Foundation Berlin-Brandenburg|Stiftung Preußische Schlösser und Gärten Berlin-Brandenburg]]'' | current_tenants = | landlord = | location = | address = | location_town = [[Berlin]] | location_country = [[Germany]] | coordinates = {{coord|52.414|13.095|display=inline}} | start_date = | completion_date = | inauguration_date = | renovation_date = | height = | floor_count = | floor_area = | main_contractor = | architect = [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]] | architecture_firm = | structural_engineer = | services_engineer = | civil_engineer = | awards = | url = [http://www.spsg.de ''Stiftung Preußische Schlösser und Gärten''] | references = | embedded = {{Infobox UNESCO World Heritage Site | child = yes | part_of = [[Palaces and Parks of Potsdam and Berlin]] | criteria = {{UNESCO WHS type|(i)(ii)(iv)}}(i)(ii)(iv) | ID = 532ter | year = 1990 | extension = 1992, 1999 }} }}
'''Glienicke Palace''' ({{lang-de|Schloss Glienicke}}) is a palace located on the peninsula of [[Berlin]]-[[Wannsee]], [[Germany]]. It was designed by [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]] for Prince [[Carl of Prussia]] in 1826.
==Location== The palace is situated near the [[Glienicke Bridge]], on the [[Bundesstraße 1]] across from the [[Jagdschloss Glienicke|Glienicke Hunting Lodge]]. Around the palace is [[Park Glienicke]].
==History== It was designed by [[Karl Friedrich Schinkel]] for Prince [[Carl of Prussia]] in 1826. The building, originally merely a cottage, was turned into a summer palace in the late [[Neoclassical architecture|Neoclassical]] style. Particularly striking are two golden lion statues in front of the frontage, which were also designed by Schinkel. The lions are versions of the ''[[Medici lions]]'' from the [[Villa Medici]]. In the palace are antique [[work of art|objets d'art]], which the Prince brought back from his trips.
==World Heritage Site== [[Image:Gemälde August Haun.jpg|thumb|225px|right|''Garden-courtyard in Glienicke'' (1837) by August C. Haun]] Since 1990, Glienicke Palace and the park have been part of the UNESCO [[World Heritage Site]] "[[Palaces and Parks of Potsdam and Berlin]]". The palace is administered by the ''[[Prussian Palaces and Gardens Foundation Berlin-Brandenburg|Stiftung Preußische Schlösser und Gärten Berlin-Brandenburg]]''. The palace's park is now called the ''Volkspark Glienicke''.
